Product Id: General Social Survey : Canadians at Work and Home
Source: Statistics Canada, General Social Survey, 2016, Canadians at Work and Home.

Satisfaction with life as a whole and with domains of life are personal subjective assessments of global and specific well-being. Respondents were asked to base their ratings on a scale of of 0 to 10, where zero means "very dissatisfied" and 10 means "very satisfied".
Average life satisfaction is the mean score based on a scale from 0 to 10.
The Atlantic provinces include Newfoundland and Labrador, Prince Edward Island, Nova Scotia, and New Brunswick.
The Prairie provinces include Manitoba, Saskatchewan and Alberta.

Personal appearance refers to weight, height or features. Please see question DOS_Q05, "On a scale from 0 to 10, where 0 means you feel "Not at all satisfied" and 10 means you are "Completely satisfied": How satisfied are you with your personal appearance, such as your weight, height, or features?".

Free time refers to the amount of time one has to do the things one likes doing. Please see question DOS_Q08, "On a scale from 0 to 10, where 0 means you feel "Not at all satisfied" and 10 means you are "Completely satisfied": How satisfied are you with the amount of time you have to do the things that you like doing?".
Quality of local environment refers to access to green space and air or water quality.
On January 16, 2018, all geography and age group values were corrected for 2016.
